{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17478895","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17478895"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:17:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:17:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18849"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18849","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18849"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.12,0.81,0.01,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11582"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79703"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11582","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11582"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18849"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65007"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5537"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"7567"},{"type":"tags","id":"9660"},{"type":"tags","id":"10785"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27253"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79703","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79703"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA paediatric registrar is preparing a presentation on newborn screening programs. The following data is available for five different congenital conditions that could potentially be included in a screening program:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECondition A: Sensitivity 99%, specificity 80%, treatment available, early treatment improves outcomes\u003Cbr /\u003ECondition B: Sensitivity 80%, specificity 99.9%, treatment available, early treatment improves outcomes\u003Cbr /\u003ECondition C: Sensitivity 99%, specificity 95%, treatment available, early treatment improves outcomes\u003Cbr /\u003ECondition D: Sensitivity 95%, specificity 99.9%, no treatment available, supportive care only\u003Cbr /\u003ECondition E: Sensitivity 99%, specificity 99.9%, treatment available but very expensive, outcomes same regardless of timing\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following conditions is most appropriate to include in a newborn screening program?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Condition A","Condition B","Condition C","Condition D","Condition E"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe World Health Organization has established criteria for screening programs, which are particularly relevant for newborn screening. These include: the condition should be an important health problem, there should be an accepted treatment, facilities for diagnosis and treatment should be available, there should be a recognisable latent stage, the natural history should be adequately understood, and there should be an agreed policy on whom to treat.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECondition A\u003C/strong\u003E has high sensitivity but relatively low specificity (80%), which would result in too many false positive results. This would lead to unnecessary anxiety for families, increased costs from confirmatory testing, and potential overburden of the healthcare system.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECondition B\u003C/strong\u003E has inadequate sensitivity (80%) which would miss 20% of cases. For newborn screening, high sensitivity is crucial to avoid missing treatable conditions in newborns where early intervention is beneficial.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECondition C\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate choice as it has high sensitivity (99%) to catch most cases, reasonable specificity (95%) to limit false positives to an acceptable level, available treatment, and improved outcomes with early intervention. This combination optimises the benefit-to-harm ratio of screening.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECondition D\u003C/strong\u003E is inappropriate for screening as there is no treatment available. Screening for untreatable conditions causes unnecessary anxiety and psychological harm to families without providing clinical benefit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECondition E\u003C/strong\u003E, while having excellent test characteristics, does not demonstrate improved outcomes with early detection. Additionally, the high cost of treatment raises concerns about cost-effectiveness and equitable access.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EExamples of conditions currently included in many newborn screening programs include phenylketonuria, congenital hypothyroidism, and cystic fibrosis, all of which have effective treatments and better outcomes with early intervention.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Newborn screening tests should have high sensitivity to minimize false negatives in conditions where early treatment improves outcomes","Conditions selected for newborn screening must have effective treatments available and clear benefits from early detection","The positive predictive value of screening tests must be balanced against the anxiety and costs of false positive results"],"references":["World Health Organization. Universal newborn screening: Implementation guidance. Geneva: World Health Organization; 2024 Apr 2. Available from: https://www.who.int/publications/i/item/9789290211389"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65007"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18849"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65007","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevi